Bigquery.FC1.name: Dataset and tables
Bigquery.FC1.description: You can create a table inside a dataset. You can run SQL queries and jobs on datasets. Jobs are actions that BigQuery runs on your behalf to load data, export data, query data, or copy data.

Bigquery.FC2.name: Routines (stored procedures or User-Defined Functions)
Bigquery.FC2.description: A routine is a reusable piece of code that can be executed within SQL queries.
Bigquery.FC2.long_description: A stored procedure is a set of statements that can be invoked by other queries or stored procedures. A User-Defined Function (UDF) lets you create a function by using an SQL expression or JavaScript code. A UDF accepts columns of input, performs actions on the input, and returns the results of those actions as values.

Bigquery.FC3.name: BigQuery connections and BigQuery Omni
Bigquery.FC3.description: To create a connection for federated queries when adding data from external data sources or exporting data to cross Cloud Storages.

Bigquery.FC4.name: BigQuery Data Transfer
Bigquery.FC4.description: You can transfer external data from SaaS applications to Google BigQuery on a regular basis.

Bigquery.FC5.name: BigQuery reservation
Bigquery.FC5.description: You can purchase dedicated query processing capacity.
Bigquery.FC5.long_description: BI Engine allows you to analyze data stored in BigQuery with sub-second query response time and high concurrency, using BI reservations.

Bigquery.FC6.name: BigQuery ML
Bigquery.FC6.description: You can create and execute machine-learning models in BigQuery using standard SQL queries.

Bigquery.FC7.name: Table snapshot
Bigquery.FC7.description: A BigQuery table snapshot preserves the contents of a table (called the base table) at a particular time.
Bigquery.FC7.long_description: A BigQuery table snapshot preserves the contents of a table (called the base table) at a particular time. You can save a snapshot of a current table or create a snapshot of a table as it was at any time in the past seven days.

Bigquery.FC8.name: Data policy
Bigquery.FC8.description: You can provide different levels of visibility to different groups of users by using policy tags.
Bigquery.FC8.long_description: Policy tags are tags with access control policies that can be applied to subresources.

Bigquery.FC9.name: Share resources via BigQuery sharing
Bigquery.FC9.description: BigQuery sharing is a data exchange platform built on top of BigQuery that enables efficient and secure sharing of data (e.g., BigQuery tables) across organizational boundaries.
Bigquery.FC9.long_description: BigQuery sharing is a data exchange platform built on top of BigQuery that enables efficient and secure sharing of data (e.g., BigQuery tables) across organizational boundaries. An exchange is a collection of data and analytics assets designed for sharing.

Bigquery.FC10.name: Subscribe to access resources via BigQuery sharing
Bigquery.FC10.description: You can subscribe to the listings.

Bigquery.T1.name: Destruction of data by deleting dataset or table
Bigquery.T1.description: A dataset is a container that holds tables and other datasets, and a table is a collection of rows and columns within a dataset, where the actual data is stored and queried. All tables within the dataset, before deletion, must be deleted either manually or by setting the deleteContents parameter to true. An attacker can delete the table or a dataset, causing a permanent loss of data.

Bigquery.T2.name: Unauthorized access to data by changing connection configurations
Bigquery.T2.description: BigQuery federations enable BigQuery to query data residing in Cloud SQL or other places in real-time, without copying or moving data. For each federation, a connection is created. An attacker can use an existing connection by viewing the connection list or sharing it with another user to get unauthorized access to tables residing in other sources.

Bigquery.T3.name: Loss of integrity and availability by copying datasets and overwriting the destination table(s)
Bigquery.T3.description: Datasets can be copied to another existing dataset. During this process, the tables in the destination dataset can be overwritten. An attacker can overwrite the destination table, causing a loss of integrity and availability.

Bigquery.T4.name: Loss of the integrity of the training model
Bigquery.T4.description: ML models are trained on data, and the accuracy of a model depends on the quantity and quality of the training data. The training data is stored in the form of tables or views. An attacker can decrease the quality of a model by adding bogus data to tables and views or by removing data from them, thereby decreasing the effectiveness of the resulting model and harming business decisions based on predictions from this model.

Bigquery.T5.name: Loss of integrity and availability by appending or overwriting data, or by creating a table
Bigquery.T5.description: Data is stored inside a BigQuery table. An attacker can create a table, overwrite table data using a load or query operation, or append additional data to an existing table by performing a load-append operation or by appending query results to the table, causing a loss of data integrity and availability.

Bigquery.T6.name: Exfiltration of data by exporting tables to other services
Bigquery.T6.description: Data can be sent to other services for storing or processing. An attacker can export data to either their destination table or a service like Cloud Storage, Data Studio, or DLP.

Bigquery.T8.name: Loss of integrity and availability by manipulating data using routines
Bigquery.T8.description: Routines (stored procedures and UDFs) allow the creation of functions using an SQL expression or JavaScript code. They accept columns of input, perform actions on the input, and return the result of those actions as a value. An attacker can write routines to perform actions like updating, deleting, and adding data to the tables. An attacker can also execute UDFs (User-Defined Functions) from unauthorized Cloud Storage for such purposes.

Bigquery.T9.name: Escalate privileges, loss of availability or integrity of data, or exfiltrate data via an unauthorized query on a dataset or table
Bigquery.T9.description: SQL queries are run on the data stored inside tables. An attacker can run a simple SQL query (e.g., "SELECT * FROM TABLE_NAME") to get all the data from a specific table or to execute unauthorized queries for different attacks (e.g., replication to an unauthorized region). An attacker can also update or drop columns in a table, change the case sensitivity of datasets and their tables to escalate privileges while avoiding detection by a poorly designed access management system, set unauthorized default values for a column to corrupt or steal data, or update the metadata cache settings of object or BigLake tables to impact the query latency.

Bigquery.T10.name: Restricting access to resources by modifying privileges
Bigquery.T10.description: IAM permissions can be used to allow users to perform actions on BigQuery resources (i.e., datasets, tables, connections, reservations, and assignments). An attacker can limit legitimate users' access to resources or allow unauthorized users to access resources by modifying the permissions.

Bigquery.T11.name: Disruption of application functionality by modification of table and view configurations
Bigquery.T11.description: Specific properties are associated with tables and views during their creation. An attacker can modify these properties (e.g., schema, expiration time, encryption key), causing downstream applications' disruption or permanent data loss.

Bigquery.T12.name: Denial of Service/Denial of Wallet by removing/creating reservations
Bigquery.T12.description: A slot is a dedicated vCPU that runs queries. Each slot is allocated to a reservation. An attacker can remove a reservation, failing any jobs that are currently executing with slots from that reservation, which may decrease the performance for future jobs, create a reservation with unauthorized configurations, modify an existing reservation to achieve the same objective, or incur additional costs by changing the assignee.

Bigquery.T13.name: Data exfiltration by updating the destination dataset in transfer and transfer credentials; or DoS by schedule manipulation
Bigquery.T13.description: The BigQuery Data Transfer Service automates data movement into BigQuery on a scheduled, managed basis using the credentials of the provided service account or the user who created or updated it. An attacker can create or update the destination dataset or transfer credentials or transfer job configuration to point to their own dataset, giving them full control over the transfer for exfiltration, create transfers of data from unauthorized sources to cause data poisoning, or modify ingestions (via schedule changes, disabling a config, altering refresh windows, creating transfers with an unauthorized encryption key), leading to Denial of Service.

Bigquery.T14.name: Loss of data during recovery by deleting a snapshot
Bigquery.T14.description: Snapshots can be used to restore previous data. An attacker (or someone by negligence) can delete snapshots to block data recovery.

Bigquery.T15.name: Data exfiltration by exporting query results
Bigquery.T15.description: BigQuery Omni uses BigQuery connections to export query results to GCP services (e.g., Spanner, BigTable, and Cloud Storage), Amazon S3, or Azure Storage. An attacker can create a connection to export query results to their GCP services, Amazon S3, or Azure Storage to exfiltrate data.

Bigquery.T17.name: Unauthorized access to the table columns by adding or removing policy tags
Bigquery.T17.description: Policy tags are attached to a column in a BigQuery table to control the visibility of sensitive data to different groups of users. An attacker can create or update a data policy or its data masking rules and associate it with a column by attaching the policy tags associated with the column policy to the column in order to escalate privileges or leak data.

Bigquery.T18.name: BigQuery ML model exfiltration
Bigquery.T18.description: BigQuery ML models can be integrated with the Vertex AI Model Registry for management purposes and exported to Cloud Storage. An attacker can register an existing model with their Vertex AI Model Registry or export it to unauthorized Cloud Storage to exfiltrate the model.

Bigquery.T19.name: Table exfiltration by cloning
Bigquery.T19.description: A table clone is a writable copy of another table. It can be created in another project within the same region. An attacker can clone a table to an unauthorized project to exfiltrate data.

Bigquery.T20.name: Exfiltration of query results to an unauthorized destination table and bucket
Bigquery.T20.description: An asynchronous job can be created, which can include various types of jobs such as query jobs, load jobs, copy jobs, and extract jobs. An attacker can execute an unauthorized query, provide an unauthorized destination table or bucket to store query results, overwrite the destination table, update the schema for the destination table, encrypt data using the DLP function with an unauthorized key, or change the encryption of the destination table.

Bigquery.T21.name: Misconfiguration of a dataset causing loss of integrity and availability, or privilege escalation by modification of the dataset's access array
Bigquery.T21.description: A dataset is a top-level container used to organize and control access to tables and views. Certain default configurations and options can be set at the organization, project, or dataset level, which indirectly affect the tables within that dataset. An attacker can create or update a dataset with unauthorized values for these configurations to cause loss of integrity and availability (e.g., setting an unauthorized value for defaultTableExpirationMs to delete a table automatically when its expirationTime is reached) or create or modify an access array for a dataset to escalate privileges.

Bigquery.T22.name: Permanent loss of a BigQuery ML model by modifying its expiration time
Bigquery.T22.description: A model's expiration time in BigQuery determines when it will be automatically deleted, serving as its "time to live" (TTL), and can also be adjusted after the model has been created. An attacker can update the expiration time of a model to cause its permanent loss.

Bigquery.T24.name: Importing malicious models in BigQuery
Bigquery.T24.description: Models can be imported from Cloud Storage buckets into BigQuery. An attacker can import a malicious or unauthorized model into BigQuery to perform harmful actions within BigQuery, affecting the integrity of the system, causing disruptions, potentially accessing and manipulating sensitive data within BigQuery, or misusing resources, such as excessive consumption of computing resources.

Bigquery.T25.name: Misconfiguration of a table to cause loss of integrity and availability
Bigquery.T25.description: A table is a primary storage structure used to hold structured data within datasets. Standard BigQuery tables store structured data directly within BigQuery, external datasets and tables reference data stored outside BigQuery, and views are logical tables built using SQL queries. An attacker can create or update a table with an unauthorized configuration to cause loss of integrity or availability (e.g., by creating or updating a materialized view with an unauthorized value for staleness to deliberately serve outdated and potentially misleading data to users or applications, which could lead to inaccurate analysis results and misinformed business decisions, by referencing an external source with corrupted data, by creating a table with an unauthorized value for expiration, or by using an unauthorized key for encryption).

Bigquery.T26.name: Unauthorized access to cached data from the last 24 hours
Bigquery.T26.description: Users can read the contents of tables within BigQuery, enabling them to query and retrieve data stored in specific tables. Results from queries against table snapshots can also be returned from the cache, even if the caller loses access to the data within the last 24 hours. An attacker can retrieve data from BigQuery tables or access the query results from the cache without making any new queries.

Bigquery.T27.name: Loss of data integrity by restoring a snapshot
Bigquery.T27.description: Snapshots are created to preserve the contents of a table at a specific time. These can be used to restore data to an existing table or a new table. An attacker can overwrite the contents of an existing table by restoring a snapshot to it.

Bigquery.T28.name: Unauthorized access to listings by setting permissions
Bigquery.T28.description: A data exchange or a listing can be subscribed to. An attacker can provide unauthorized subscribers with access to a listing's content by setting permissions for listings at the project, data exchange, or listing level.

Bigquery.T29.name: Denial of Service by revoking subscriptions
Bigquery.T29.description: A subscription is created upon subscribing to a listing. An attacker can revoke a subscription for a legitimate subscriber, causing Denial of Service to the subscriber.

Bigquery.T30.name: Unauthorized access to contents of a listing
Bigquery.T30.description: A listing contains BigQuery resources (e.g., tables, models, views) or a Pub/Sub topic that is published within a data exchange. An attacker can create a public listing to provide access to its content or launch an attack against subscribers by phishing (e.g., providing their own email ID or URL) in primaryContact, requestAccess, dataProvider, or publisher.

Bigquery.T31.name: Discovery of BigQuery sharing resources
Bigquery.T31.description: Email IDs are configured for the provider, publisher, and subscriber of a data exchange and listing. An attacker can gather these and launch attacks against them.

Bigquery.T32.name: Denial of Service by deleting data exchanges, listings, or subscriptions
Bigquery.T32.description: A data exchange, its individual listings, and their subscriptions can be deleted. Data exchanges and listings with active Pub/Sub subscriptions can't be deleted. An attacker can delete any of these resources to cause Denial of Service for their subscribers.

Bigquery.T33.name: Email leakage via malicious listing
Bigquery.T33.description: When a subscriber subscribes to a listing, a linked source is created in the subscriber's project, which acts as a reference or pointer to the source in the provider's project. An attacker can subscribe to a malicious public listing, impersonating a legitimate provider to share their email IDs and launch further attacks.

Bigquery.T34.name: Denial of Service via unauthorized continuous query cancellation
Bigquery.T34.description: Continuous queries in BigQuery can be long-lived jobs that perform real-time analytics, ML inference, or replication into downstream systems. An attacker can disrupt these pipelines by continuously canceling active queries, causing loss of analytics, halting data replication, and triggering operational downtime for dependent applications.

Bigquery.T35.name: Expose sensitive data via auto-enabled Gemini API
Bigquery.T35.description: The Gemini for Google Cloud API is enabled by default in BigQuery projects linked to accounts based in supported locations unless explicitly opted out. An attacker can exploit Gemini integrations to prompt, extract, or process sensitive data outside BigQuery via AI features without clear user awareness or guardrails.

Bigquery.T36.name: Data corruption via unauthorized hard failover
Bigquery.T36.description: Users can promote a BigQuery reservation's secondary region to primary, with options for soft or hard failover. An attacker can initiate a hard failover without waiting for full data replication, resulting in some data corruption.

Bigquery.CO5.description: Restrict access to columns and protect sensitive data

Bigquery.CO6.description: Restrict access to rows with BigQuery row-level security

Bigquery.CO7.description: Encrypt resources (e.g., datasets, models, data transfers) with customer-managed encryption keys and protect the keys

Bigquery.CO8.description: Enforce authorized configurations on BigQuery datasets, tables, reservations, assignments, asynchronous query jobs, BigQuery sharing's data exchanges, and listings

Bigquery.CO9.description: De-identify sensitive data using Cloud DLP

Bigquery.CO10.description: Secure the authorized sources and destinations used for datasets, tables, models, connections, jobs, and listings

Bigquery.CO12.description: Set the expiration time of BigQuery tables as per the requirements

Bigquery.CO15.description: Enable logs for BigQuery Data Transfer

Bigquery.CO16.description: Monitor data protection, data ingestion, and data quality

Bigquery.CO17.description: Register BigQuery models as per the requirements

Bigquery.CO18.description: Limit the amount of cloned data

Bigquery.CO22.description: Secure and use the authorized sources and their respective authorized configurations with BigQuery Data Transfer

Bigquery.CO24.description: Enforce secure SDLC processes on routines and queries

Bigquery.CO25.description: Set an authorized expiration time for each ML model

Bigquery.CO26.description: Use fingerprinting for ML models to ensure their integrity

Bigquery.CO27.description: Ensure sensitive data is not added in the listing fields

Bigquery.CO28.description: Enforce access to sensitive data via data clean rooms

Bigquery.CO29.description: Restrict access to listings and data exchanges to authorized subscribers only

Bigquery.CO30.description: Restrict and manage subscriptions to authorized listings and data exchanges only

Bigquery.CO31.description: Restrict the export of data by enabling restricted export

Bigquery.CO32.description: Enforce authorized access entities only, change management, and secure decommissioning on datasets

Bigquery.CO33.description: Define and enforce BigQuery configuration baselines at the organization and project levels

Bigquery.CO34.description: Restrict and manage Gemini in BigQuery projects

Bigquery.C1.description: Limit the access to the IAM actions required to perform attacks, following the IAM Operating Model and using the IAM ThreatModel.
Bigquery.C1.testing: Request the list of authorized IAM members that have the permissions required to launch attacks, its review process, and its review records.

Bigquery.C2.description: Enforce VPC origin (e.g., using DNS redirection on a VPC-based proxy) following the Compute ThreatModel.
Bigquery.C2.testing: Request how the Compute ThreatModel is applied for enforcing VPC origin.

Bigquery.C3.description: Define the requirements for the backup of each BigQuery dataset, table, and model.
Bigquery.C3.testing: Request the backup requirements for each BigQuery dataset, table, and model.

Bigquery.C4.description: Ensure each BigQuery dataset, table, and model is backed up (e.g., by creating snapshots or exports) according to the requirements and is restorable.
Bigquery.C4.testing: Request the mechanism ensuring BigQuery datasets, tables, and models are backed up (e.g., by creating snapshots or exports) according to their requirements, the evidence of their execution, and their regular testing of restoration.

Bigquery.C5.description: Verify all BigQuery datasets, tables, and models are backed up according to the requirements.
Bigquery.C5.testing: Change the backup mechanism to be outside the requirements; it should be detected.

Bigquery.C6.description: Maintain a list of authorized IAM entities allowed to access the tables, views, and table data in a specific dataset (note: columns can be made case-sensitive, and a default value can be set for columns).
Bigquery.C6.testing: Request the list of authorized IAM entities allowed to access the tables, views, and table data in a specific dataset, its review process, and its review records.

Bigquery.C7.description: Ensure only authorized IAM entities are allowed to access the tables, views, and table data in each dataset.
Bigquery.C7.testing: Request 1) the mechanism ensuring only authorized IAM entities are allowed to access the tables, views, and table data in a specific dataset, 2) its records of execution for all new IAM entities, and 3) the plan to move any older IAM entities.

Bigquery.C8.description: Verify only authorized IAM entities are allowed to access the tables, views, and table data in each dataset.
Bigquery.C8.testing: Configure an unauthorized IAM entity to have access to 1) a table or 2) a view; it should be detected.

Bigquery.C9.description: Define the criteria for the sensitivity of columns in each table and each view, and their requirements for data protection (e.g., using BigQuery column-level security, column-level data masking, custom masking routines, restriction analysis rules, list overlap analysis rules, aggregation threshold analysis rules, differential privacy clauses, or data clean rooms).
Bigquery.C9.testing: Request the criteria for the sensitivity of columns in a table and each view and their requirements for data protection.

Bigquery.C10.description: Ensure only authorized IAM entities are allowed to access sensitive columns of tables and views.
Bigquery.C10.testing: Request 1) the mechanism ensuring only authorized IAM entities are allowed to access sensitive columns of tables and views, 2) its records of execution for all new IAM entities, and 3) the plan to move any older IAM entities.

Bigquery.C11.description: Verify only authorized IAM entities are allowed to access sensitive columns of each table and each view.
Bigquery.C11.testing: Configure an unauthorized IAM entity with access to a sensitive column; it should be detected.

Bigquery.C12.description: Define the criteria for the sensitivity of rows in each table.
Bigquery.C12.testing: Request the criteria for the sensitivity of rows in a table.

Bigquery.C13.description: Ensure only authorized IAM entities are allowed to access sensitive rows of a table (e.g., using BigQuery row-level security).
Bigquery.C13.testing: Request 1) the mechanism ensuring only authorized IAM entities are allowed to access sensitive rows of a table, 2) its records of execution for all new IAM entities, and 3) the plan to move any older IAM entities.

Bigquery.C14.description: Verify only authorized IAM entities are allowed to access sensitive rows of a table.
Bigquery.C14.testing: Configure an unauthorized IAM entity with access to a sensitive row; it should be detected.

Bigquery.C15.description: Ensure no dataset is accessible to "AllUsers" or "AllAuthenticatedUsers", except if allowed.
Bigquery.C15.testing: Request 1) the mechanism ensuring no dataset is accessible to "AllUsers" or "AllAuthenticatedUsers", 2) its records of execution for all datasets, and 3) the plan to move any older datasets.

Bigquery.C16.description: Verify no dataset is accessible to "AllUsers" or "AllAuthenticatedUsers" (e.g., using the Security Command Center finding PUBLIC_DATASET).
Bigquery.C16.testing: Modify a dataset to allow access to 1) "AllUsers", or 2) "AllAuthenticatedUsers"; it should be detected.

Bigquery.C17.description: Define the authorized configuration (i.e., defaultTableExpirationMs, defaultPartitionExpirationMs, defaultEncryptionConfiguration, linkedDatasetSource, externalDatasetReference, defaultCollation, defaultRoundingMode, maxTimeTravelHours, storageBillingModel, and defaultEncryptionConfiguration) for each BigQuery dataset.
Bigquery.C17.testing: Request the authorized configuration for each BigQuery dataset, its review process, and its review records.

Bigquery.C18.description: Ensure the configuration of each BigQuery dataset is authorized.
Bigquery.C18.testing: Request the mechanism ensuring the configuration of each BigQuery dataset is authorized, and the evidence of its execution.

Bigquery.C19.description: Verify all BigQuery datasets have authorized configurations.
Bigquery.C19.testing: Create a dataset with an unauthorized configuration; it should be detected.

Bigquery.C20.description: Ensure sensitive data is identified and redacted (e.g., using Cloud DLP).
Bigquery.C20.testing: Request the mechanism to identify and redact sensitive data.

Bigquery.C21.description: Verify sensitive data is identified and redacted (e.g., using Cloud DLP).
Bigquery.C21.testing: Add non-redacted sensitive data; it should be detected.

Bigquery.C22.description: Maintain a list of authorized sources and destinations (e.g., Cloud Storage, BigQuery, Vertex AI (for LLM, via BigQuery connection only)) to be used with each dataset, table, model, connection, job, and listing.
Bigquery.C22.testing: Request the list of all authorized sources and destinations to be used with each dataset, table, model, connection, job, and listing, its review process, and its review records.

Bigquery.C23.description: Ensure each dataset, table, model, connection, job, and listing uses authorized sources and destinations.
Bigquery.C23.testing: Request 1) the mechanism ensuring only authorized sources and destinations are configured, 2) its records of execution for all new sources and destinations, and 3) the plan to move any older sources and destinations.

Bigquery.C24.description: Verify each dataset, table, model, connection, job, and listing uses authorized sources and destinations.
Bigquery.C24.testing: For a BigQuery dataset, table, model, connection, job, or listing, use an unauthorized 1) source or 2) destination; it should be detected.

Bigquery.C25.description: Protect the sources and destinations used by each table, model, connection, job, and listing, using their respective services' ThreatModels.
Bigquery.C25.testing: Request how the respective source and destination ThreatModels are applied to BigQuery.

Bigquery.C26.description: Maintain a list of authorized CMEKs to be used with each BigQuery resource (e.g., dataset, DLP function, model, data transfer), ideally dedicated (e.g., using Autokey on bigquery.googleapis.com/Dataset), and of the default CMEK at the project or organization level, and define the requirement to rotate key versions for tables.
Bigquery.C26.testing: Request the list of authorized CMEKs and their versions to be used by the BigQuery resource and the default CMEK per project or at the organization level, and the requirement to rotate key versions for tables, their review process, and their review records.

Bigquery.C27.description: Ensure only authorized CMEKs and their versions are used with the BigQuery resource.
Bigquery.C27.testing: Request 1) the mechanism ensuring only authorized CMEKs are configured, 2) its records of execution for all new BigQuery resources, and 3) the plan to move any older BigQuery resources.

Bigquery.C28.description: Protect the CMEKs used by each BigQuery resource using the Cloud KMS ThreatModel (including enforcing CMEK protection using organization policy constraints/gcp.restrictCmekCryptoKeyProjects and constraints/gcp.restrictNonCmekServices as per Cloudkms.C32 and Cloudkms.C34).
Bigquery.C28.testing: Request how the Cloud KMS ThreatModel is applied to BigQuery resources.

Bigquery.C29.description: Verify each BigQuery resource is encrypted using an authorized CMEK and its version.
Bigquery.C29.testing: Use an unauthorized 1) CMEK or a 2) version with a BigQuery resource; it should be detected.

Bigquery.C32.description: Define the requirements for the expiration time of each BigQuery table.
Bigquery.C32.testing: Request the requirements for the expiration time of each BigQuery table.

Bigquery.C33.description: Ensure the expiration time of each BigQuery table is set according to the requirements.
Bigquery.C33.testing: Request the mechanism ensuring the expiration time of each BigQuery table is set according to its requirements.

Bigquery.C34.description: Verify the expiration time of each BigQuery table is set to its requirements.
Bigquery.C34.testing: Set the expiration time of a BigQuery table to be outside its requirements; it should be detected.

Bigquery.C35.description: Monitor slot consumption (e.g., using slot recommender), job concurrency, job execution time, job errors, and bytes processed across the entire organization (e.g., using BigQuery Admin Resource Charts).
Bigquery.C35.testing: Create a job and use slots in an abnormal way; it should be detected.

Bigquery.C36.description: Ensure AEAD encryption functions are used to encrypt data at the column level.
Bigquery.C36.testing: Request the mechanism ensuring AEAD encryption functions are used to encrypt data at the column level.

Bigquery.C37.description: Verify AEAD encryption functions are used to encrypt data at the column level.
Bigquery.C37.testing: Do not encrypt the data at the column level; it should be detected.

Bigquery.C38.description: Define the requirements for using BigQuery Omni (AWS and/or Azure).
Bigquery.C38.testing: Request the requirements for the use of BigQuery Omni.

Bigquery.C39.description: Ensure the use of BigQuery Omni as per the requirements (e.g., using organizational constraints constraints/bigquery.disableBQOmniAWS and constraints/bigquery.disableBQOmniAzure).
Bigquery.C39.testing: Request the implementation to ensure the use of BigQuery Omni as per the requirements and its records of execution.

Bigquery.C40.description: Verify the use of BigQuery Omni as per the requirements.
Bigquery.C40.testing: Use BigQuery Omni outside the requirements; it should be detected.

Bigquery.C41.description: Ensure Cloud Audit Logs for BigQuery Data Transfer are enabled (ref).
Bigquery.C41.testing: Request the implementation for enabling the Cloud Audit Logs for BigQuery Data Transfer and its records for execution.

Bigquery.C42.description: Monitor the abnormal number of concurrent connections and throughput for the BigQuery table (e.g., by using the Monitoring metric CONSUMER QUOTA - QUOTA LIMIT).
Bigquery.C42.testing: Create 1) an abnormal number of concurrent connections and 2) abnormal throughput for a BigQuery table; it should be detected.

Bigquery.C43.description: Monitor slot capacity (e.g., using the slot estimator) to estimate the correct number of slots for the BigQuery workload.
Bigquery.C43.testing: Increase or decrease slot capacity widely; it should be detected.

Bigquery.C44.testing: Request the criteria for using data policies for each column in each table.

Bigquery.C45.testing: Request 1) the mechanism ensuring only authorized IAM entities are allowed to access sensitive columns of a table with data policies, 2) its records of execution for all new IAM entities, and 3) the plan to move any older IAM entities.

Bigquery.C46.description: Verify only authorized IAM entities are allowed to access sensitive columns of a table by using data policies.
Bigquery.C46.testing: Configure an unauthorized IAM entity with access to a sensitive column in a data policy; it should be detected.

Bigquery.C47.description: Define the requirements to register the BigQuery models with the Vertex AI Model Registry for each BigQuery model.
Bigquery.C47.testing: Request the registration requirements for each BigQuery model.

Bigquery.A1.action_description: Gets the access control policy for a resource. Returns an empty policy if the resource exists and does not have a policy set.

Bigquery.A2.action_description: Updates information in an existing table. The update method replaces the entire table resource, whereas the patch method only replaces fields that are provided in the submitted table resource. This method supports patch semantics.

Bigquery.A3.action_description: Returns permissions that a caller has on the specified resource. If the resource does not exist, this will return an empty set of permissions, not a not_found error.

Bigquery.A4.action_description: Updates information in an existing table. The update method replaces the entire table resource, whereas the patch method only replaces fields that are provided in the submitted table resource.

Bigquery.A5.action_description: Creates a new, empty table in the dataset.

Bigquery.A6.action_description: Gets the specified table resource by table ID. This method does not return the data in the table, it only returns the table resource, which describes the structure of this table.

Bigquery.A7.action_description: Sets the access control policy on the specified resource. Replaces any existing policy.

Bigquery.A8.action_description: Lists all tables in the specified dataset.

Bigquery.A9.action_description: Deletes the table specified by tableid from the dataset. If the table contains data, all the data will be deleted.

Bigquery.A12.action_description: Export table data out of BigQuery.

Bigquery.A14.action_description: Set policy tags in table schema.

Bigquery.A16.action_description: Streams data into BigQuery one record at a time without needing to run a load job.

Bigquery.A17.action_description: Retrieves table data from a specified set of rows.

Bigquery.A18.action_description: Returns information about a specific job. Job information is available for a six-month period after creation.

Bigquery.A20.action_description: Lists all jobs that you started in the specified project. Job information is available for a six-month period after creation. The job list is sorted in reverse chronological order, by job creation time.

Bigquery.A21.action_description: List all jobs and retrieve metadata on any job submitted by any user.

Bigquery.A22.action_description: Requests that a job be cancelled. This call will return immediately, and the client will need to poll for the job status to see if the cancel completed successfully.

Bigquery.A23.action_description: Requests that a job is deleted. This call will return when the job is deleted. This method is available in limited preview.

Bigquery.A24.action_description: Runs a BigQuery SQL query synchronously and returns query results if the query completes within a specified timeout.

Bigquery.A25.action_description: Retrieves the results of a query job.

Bigquery.A26.action_description: Lists all routines in the specified dataset.

Bigquery.A27.action_description: Gets the specified routine resource by routine ID.

Bigquery.A28.action_description: Creates a new routine in the dataset.

Bigquery.A29.action_description: Deletes the routine specified by routineid from the dataset.

Bigquery.A30.action_description: Updates information in an existing routine. The update method replaces the entire routine resource.

Bigquery.A31.action_description: Returns the dataset specified by datasetid.

Bigquery.A32.action_description: Updates information in an existing dataset. The update method replaces the entire dataset resource, whereas the patch method only replaces fields that are provided in the submitted dataset resource. This method supports patch semantics.

Bigquery.A33.action_description: Lists all datasets in the specified project.

Bigquery.A34.action_description: Deletes the dataset specified by the datasetid value. Before you can delete a dataset, you must delete all its tables, either manually or by specifying deleteContents. Immediately after deletion, you can create another dataset with the same name.

Bigquery.A36.action_description: Updates information in an existing dataset. The update method replaces the entire dataset resource, whereas the patch method only replaces fields that are provided in the submitted dataset resource.

Bigquery.A37.action_description: Read a dataset's IAM permissions (via the console).

Bigquery.A38.action_description: Change a dataset's IAM permissions (via the console).

Bigquery.A40.action_description: Create a new row-level access policy on a table.

Bigquery.A41.action_description: Delete a row-level access policy from a table.

Bigquery.A42.action_description: Gets data in a table that you want to be visible only to the members of a row-level access policy's grantee list. We recommend this permission only be granted on a row-level access policy resource.

Bigquery.A44.action_description: Returns permissions that a caller has on the specified resource. If the resource does not exist, this will return an empty set of permissions, not a not_found error.

Bigquery.A45.action_description: Gets the access control policy for a resource. Returns an empty policy if the resource exists and does not have a policy set.

Bigquery.A46.action_description: Lists all row access policies on the specified table.

Bigquery.A47.action_description: Sets the access control policy on the specified resource. Replaces any existing policy.

Bigquery.A48.action_description: Returns the email address of the service account for your project used for interactions with Google Cloud KMS.

Bigquery.A56.action_description: Lists all models in the specified dataset.

Bigquery.A103.action_description: Merges capacity commitments of the same plan into a single commitment. The resulting capacity commitment has the greater commitment_end_time out of the to-be-merged capacity commitments. Attempting to merge capacity commitments of different plan will fail with the error code google. Rpc. Code. Failed_precondition.

Bigquery.A104.action_description: Lists all the capacity commitments for the admin project.

Bigquery.A105.action_description: Creates a new capacity commitment resource.

Bigquery.A106.action_description: Splits capacity commitment to two commitments of the same plan and commitment_end_time. A common use case is to enable downgrading commitments. For example, in order to downgrade from 10000 slots to 8000, you might split a 10000 capacity commitment into commitments of 2000 and 8000. Then, you would change the plan of the first one to flex and then delete it.

Bigquery.A107.action_description: Deletes a capacity commitment. Attempting to delete capacity commitment before its commitment_end_time will fail with the error code google. Rpc. Code. Failed_precondition.

Bigquery.A108.action_description: Updates an existing capacity commitment. Only plan and renewal_plan fields can be updated. Plan can only be changed to a plan of a longer commitment period. Attempting to change to a plan with shorter commitment period will fail with the error code google. Rpc. Code. Failed_precondition.

Bigquery.A109.action_description: Creates an assignment object which allows the given project to submit jobs of a certain type using slots from the specified reservation.

Bigquery.A111.action_description: Lists assignments. Only explicitly created assignments will be returned.

Bigquery.A112.action_description: Moves an assignment under a new reservation. This differs from removing an existing assignment and recreating a new one by providing a transactional change that ensures an assignee always has an associated reservation.

Bigquery.A113.action_description: Lists all the reservations for the project in the specified location.

Bigquery.A115.action_description: Deletes a reservation. Returns google. Rpc. Code. Failed_precondition when reservation has assignments.

Bigquery.A119.action_description: Looks up assignments for a specified resource for a particular region. If the request is about a project: 1. Assignments created on the project will be returned if they exist. 2. Otherwise assignments created on the closest ancestor will be returned. 3. Assignments for different jobtypes will all be returned. The same logic applies if the request is about a folder. If the request is about an organization, then assignments created on the organization will be returned (organization doesn't have ancestors).

Bigquery.A120.action_description: Updates a BI reservation. Only fields specified in the field_mask are updated. A singleton BI reservation always exists with default size 0. In order to reserve BI capacity it needs to be updated to an amount greater than 0. In order to release BI Capacity Reservation size must be set to 0.

Bigquery.A121.action_description: Looks up assignments for a specified resource for a particular region. If the request is about a project: 1. Assignments created on the project will be returned if they exist. 2. Otherwise assignments created on the closest ancestor will be returned. 3. Assignments for different jobtypes will all be returned. The same logic applies if the request is about a folder. If the request is about an organization, then assignments created on the organization will be returned (organization doesn't have ancestors).
